From 96952fc93b2d4395c6430cee4fdb1584ccf7d9f1 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <claude@anthropic.com>
Date: Thu, 23 Jul 2026 04:21:21 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Fix offload/reload test methodology; extend Algorithm with
 lr/param/decay

Two related but independent threads from real-XPU testing feedback.

=== Thread 1: fix a false test failure ===

smoke_test_composed_adafactor.py failed on real XPU hardware: "loss
degraded after round trip: 0.000001 -> 0.003671" for both strategies.
Investigated rather than assumed real: AdafactorAlgorithm's gradient-
normalized update doesn't shrink its own step size as loss shrinks
(unlike raw-gradient SGD), so once training converges very tightly (it
reached ~1e-6 loss on this toy problem on the user's XPU run), it keeps
taking full-sized steps and legitimately oscillates around the optimum.
Confirmed this happens with ZERO offload/reload involved at all, just
continued training (direct reproduction: loss bounces between ~1e-12
and ~5e-2 continuously). The test's old check compared resumed loss
against the loss immediately before offload, which happened to be
sampled right at a lucky near-zero point -- comparing noise to noise.

Fixed in both smoke_test_composed_came.py and
smoke_test_composed_adafactor.py:
1. Added a direct, much stronger check: snapshot state before offload,
   compare with torch.equal() after reload -- independent of any
   downstream training dynamics entirely.
2. Changed the training-continues check to compare resumed loss against
   the ORIGINAL starting loss, not the fragile near-offload value.

Verified the fix still discriminates: simulated a real corruption
(substituting reset_states() for the round trip) and confirmed the new
check catches it, before confirming it doesn't change what CAME's own
already-passing real-XPU numbers report.

=== Thread 2: universal Algorithm contract (lr, param, decay) ===

Prompted by a real report: scale_parameter=True appeared to make almost
no training progress. Investigated before touching code: its effective
step size is clamp(param_rms**2, min=~1e-6) * lr -- for a parameter
initialized at or near zero (LoRA's B matrix, by convention, starts at
exactly zero), this collapses to ~1e-6 * lr and stays there indefinitely
(self-reinforcing: near-zero updates keep the parameter near zero, which
keeps the floor active). Confirmed both this port and the legacy
reference reproduce the identical floor value -- not a bug, a real
documented pathology of the algorithm interacting with zero-init
parameters.

Given that, and an explicit ask for a more versatile/universal design
rather than a special case: Algorithm.compute_update() now receives
`param` (read-only) and `lr`, and returns `(delta, decay)` instead of a
bare update -- delta is the final, already-lr-scaled amount to subtract;
decay is None or a multiplicative factor an ExecutionStrategy applies to
param.data before subtracting delta, matching every legacy optimizer's
own decay-then-step order. Algorithm still never mutates param directly.

What this unlocked:
- AdafactorAlgorithm implements scale_parameter (both settings) and
  weight_decay for real. ComposedAdafactorOptimizerNode exposes both as
  ports, defaulted OFF (not the legacy wrapper's scale_parameter=True,
  weight_decay=1.0) so existing tested toy-regression behavior doesn't
  silently change -- pass both explicitly for legacy parity.
- CAMEAlgorithm gained weight_decay support essentially for free -- it
  never needed lr/param itself, but folding lr into its own return value
  and adding decay through the same generic mechanism cost almost
  nothing. Real feature parity CAME's port didn't have before.
  ComposedCAMEOptimizerNode's weight_decay defaults to 0.0, matching the
  legacy wrapper exactly -- no behavior change for existing callers.
- Both strategies updated to the new call site, mechanically.

Verified: extended smoke_test_adafactor_equivalence.py to cover the full
config surface against core.optimizers.ChunkedXPUAdafactor directly --
scale_parameter on/off, weight_decay on/off (including the legacy
default combination), momentum on/off, both strategies, float32 and
bf16. All pass, float32 to ~6e-8-2e-6, bf16 to ordinary rounding-noise
levels. New smoke_test_came_equivalence.py does the same for
CAMEAlgorithm against core.optimizers.ChunkedXPUCAME directly -- the
first time this class was checked against real tensors rather than the
original external-reference numpy mock. float32 ~4e-6 (with or without
decay, confirmed identical); bf16 shows a real, bounded, non-exploding
divergence present identically with weight_decay=0 (so unrelated to
this change) -- noted as a new data point, not chased further.

All 6 smoke tests pass (CPU). Neither Adafactor test has run on real XPU
yet -- next concrete step, per docs/nodes_package_design.md.
